                        <scopecontent>
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                                 <p>Emanuel Hertz (1870-1940), a New York lawyer, spoke and published extensively on Lincoln. He brought together many of his writings in <emph render="italic">Abraham Lincoln: A New Portrait </emph>(2 vols., 1931).</p>
                                 <p>Hertz was also active in the Weik Manuscript Corporation which was engaged in selling the Herndon-Weik collection from the estate of Jesse W. Weik (1857-1930). The collection was apparently held between 1933 and 1938 by G. A. Baker and Company which valued it as $100,000, then bought privately, and finally given to the Library of Congress in 1941.</p>
                                 <p>Meanwhile, Hertz published &quot;a minor portion&quot; of the collection in <emph render="italic">The Hidden Lincoln from the Letters and Papers of William H. Herndon</emph> (1938), a volume judged by James G. Randall (and others) to be &quot;poorly selected and unskillfuly edited&quot; (<emph render="italic">Lincoln the President</emph> [1945], 2:350).</p>
                                 <p>The Hertz collection itself contains a file of his correspondence, mainly related to the Herndon-Weik archive. The collection also contains 23 articles and addresses written by Hertz (all of which are listed in Jay Monaghan, comp., <emph render="italic">Lincoln Bibliography, 1839-1939</emph> [2 vols., 1943-45], and other copies of which have been separately cataloged). Finally, the Hertz collection includes a file of his clippings related to Lincoln and a list of manuscripts, photostats of which he obtained from the Ward Hill Lamon collection in the Huntington Library. (The Hertz collection, except for the articles, was initially bound at the University of Illinois Library as Vol. VIII of the Randall collection.)</p>
                                 <p>Hertz also arranged for the University of Illinois to photostat a large number of items in the Herndon-Weik collection for Randall&#039;s use. See the entry in this database for the Randall collection.</p>
                        </scopecontent>
            


